Completed slice:
- 2026-05-15: Vite plugin package added under `plugins/vite`; it watches Linguini config/schema/locale files, runs `linguini build`, invalidates generated modules, and emits a `linguini:update` HMR event.
- 2026-05-15: LSP quick fixes now convert analyzer `QuickFix` replacement and command data into generic code actions, so new analyzer quick fixes do not need per-fix LSP code.
- 2026-05-15: Analyzer quick fixes now cover missing enum branches, missing `other` branches, missing locale message stubs, and ambiguous implicit plural arguments with multiple explicit argument variants.
- 2026-05-15: Formatter enforces configured line width for long structural argument lists while preserving raw text lines.
- 2026-05-15: VS Code formatting now goes through LSP only; removed shell-out formatter provider and stale formatter settings.
- 2026-05-15: Formatter core split into custom `FormatIr` plus token-to-IR lowering/rendering modules while preserving schema/locale idempotency behavior.
- 2026-05-15: LSP rename now targets the cursor identifier and edits matching identifiers across all open Linguini schema/locale documents; rename refactor action added.
- 2026-05-15: VS Code extension now prefers package-time bundled native server binary at `server/<platform>-<arch>/linguini(.exe)` and falls back to `linguini` on PATH.
- 2026-05-15: Removed generated server binaries from git tracking; `editors/vscode/server/` is ignored and filled during package builds.

Implementation decisions:
- Vite plugin is dependency-light ESM JavaScript with `.d.ts` types; it shells to `linguini build` by default and supports an injected `build` function for tests/custom integrations.
- LSP quick-fix support is analyzer-driven: replacement fixes become workspace edits, command-only fixes become command code actions, and multiple fixes on one diagnostic are exposed as separate actions.
- Formatter line-width enforcement intentionally targets structural parenthesized lines only; raw text lines are not wrapped because that would change message semantics.
- Extension formatting must rely on the LSP `textDocument/formatting` capability; no separate formatter process or `linguini formatting` command.
- Native server bundling is per built VSIX/platform: `npm run build:server` builds host binary, and `npm run build:server:target -- <vscode-target>` builds a selected VS Code target into `editors/vscode/server/<target>/`.
- Supported native VS Code targets in the build script: `darwin-arm64`, `darwin-x64`, `linux-arm64`, `linux-armhf`, `linux-x64`, `alpine-arm64`, `alpine-x64`, `win32-arm64`, `win32-ia32`, `win32-x64`.
- User override remains possible: if `linguini.server.path` is anything other than default `linguini`, the extension uses that exact path.
- Formatter IR is layout-oriented, not semantic IR: tokens lower into text, spacing, hard-line, indent/dedent, raw-line-start, and selector-arm marker items before rendering.
- LSP rename remains token/name based across open documents; full project indexing and schema-aware rename validation are still future work.

